\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Geometry contrast between sycophancy and gender across completed layers 4, 8, and 12. This is a focused contrast between the primary nonlinear case and the diagnostic baseline, not an all-dataset geometry census. The table reports two quantities: a local intrinsic-dimension range and the mean angle between a global concept direction and local per-sample concept directions. Under the manifold framing, large local-global angles indicate that a single global direction is a poor first-order summary across neighborhoods. They do not by themselves provide a direct estimate of curvature. Sycophancy shows substantially larger local-global misalignment than gender, supporting it as the primary case for locally adaptive, manifold-motivated erasure methods.}}{12}{table.caption.36}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:geometry_contrast_summary}{{6}{12}{Geometry contrast between sycophancy and gender across completed layers 4, 8, and 12. This is a focused contrast between the primary nonlinear case and the diagnostic baseline, not an all-dataset geometry census. The table reports two quantities: a local intrinsic-dimension range and the mean angle between a global concept direction and local per-sample concept directions. Under the manifold framing, large local-global angles indicate that a single global direction is a poor first-order summary across neighborhoods. They do not by themselves provide a direct estimate of curvature. Sycophancy shows substantially larger local-global misalignment than gender, supporting it as the primary case for locally adaptive, manifold-motivated erasure methods}{table.caption.36}{}}
\newlabel{fig:q1_transfer}{{2a}{12}{Q1: cross-domain linear subspace transfer (top-1 next-token agreement, $k \approx m_{\mathrm {src}}$). Each cell measures how well target-domain representations are preserved when projected onto the global PCA subspace of the source domain. High diagonal values confirm per-domain subspace self-sufficiency. Sycophancy is the structural outlier: near-zero transfer into sycophancy from biasbios ($0.002$) and code ($0.13$) charts indicates that its global support is not well summarized by those other task charts}{figure.caption.38}{}}
\newlabel{sub@fig:q1_transfer}{{a}{12}{Q1: cross-domain linear subspace transfer (top-1 next-token agreement, $k \approx m_{\mathrm {src}}$). Each cell measures how well target-domain representations are preserved when projected onto the global PCA subspace of the source domain. High diagonal values confirm per-domain subspace self-sufficiency. Sycophancy is the structural outlier: near-zero transfer into sycophancy from biasbios ($0.002$) and code ($0.13$) charts indicates that its global support is not well summarized by those other task charts}{figure.caption.38}{}}
\newlabel{fig:q2_sensitivity}{{2b}{12}{Q2: subspace sensitivity (off/on top-1 agreement ratio, $\epsilon = 0.5$). Values above~1 (red) indicate that on-subspace perturbations are more disruptive than equally sized off-subspace perturbations, confirming the subspace as the primary carrier of task-relevant computation. Sycophancy diagonal ($1.16$, darkest red) shows the strongest sensitivity asymmetry. Blue off-diagonal entries in the sycophancy column ($0.79$, $0.72$) confirm that the sycophancy subspace is a null direction for biasbios and code predictions}{figure.caption.38}{}}
\newlabel{sub@fig:q2_sensitivity}{{b}{12}{Q2: subspace sensitivity (off/on top-1 agreement ratio, $\epsilon = 0.5$). Values above~1 (red) indicate that on-subspace perturbations are more disruptive than equally sized off-subspace perturbations, confirming the subspace as the primary carrier of task-relevant computation. Sycophancy diagonal ($1.16$, darkest red) shows the strongest sensitivity asymmetry. Blue off-diagonal entries in the sycophancy column ($0.79$, $0.72$) confirm that the sycophancy subspace is a null direction for biasbios and code predictions}{figure.caption.38}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Geometric diagnostics at layer~8 of Qwen2.5-0.5B across five domains (biasbios, code, math, safety, sycophancy). Rows index the target domain whose representations are evaluated; columns index the source domain whose global PCA subspace is applied. \textbf  {Left (Q1):} linear subspace transfer matrix. \textbf  {Right (Q2):} subspace sensitivity ratio. Both experiments use 500 evaluation samples per domain with 2{,}000 additional held-out samples for intrinsic-dimension estimation.}}{12}{figure.caption.38}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:geom_combined}{{2}{12}{Geometric diagnostics at layer~8 of Qwen2.5-0.5B across five domains (biasbios, code, math, safety, sycophancy). Rows index the target domain whose representations are evaluated; columns index the source domain whose global PCA subspace is applied. \textbf {Left (Q1):} linear subspace transfer matrix. \textbf {Right (Q2):} subspace sensitivity ratio. Both experiments use 500 evaluation samples per domain with 2{,}000 additional held-out samples for intrinsic-dimension estimation}{figure.caption.38}{}}
